Maria Ressa of the Philippines and Dmitry Muratov of Russia have been awarded the Nobel Peace Prize for their relentless pursuit of truth and commitment to the principles of a free press. They have worked to expose corruption and demand transparency, facing constant threats, harassment, and legal action. Their recognition sheds light on the increasing pressure faced by journalists and freedom of expression worldwide. The Nobel Committee's decision brings attention to the important role journalists play in upholding democracy.